<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0039</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Natalie </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Papanastasiou</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, PhD candidate, Social Policy, School of Social and Political Science, University of Edinburgh. Funded by the Economic and Social Research Council. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">E-mail: </span><a href="mailto:n.papanastasiou@sms.ed.ac.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">n.papanastasiou@sms.ed.ac.uk</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.1 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The evidence presented in this paper is based on research which involved conducting 30 interviews with local authority officers, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">academy </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">sponsors, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">academy </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">principals and chairs of governors. Interviews </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">explored</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> the local implementation of the academies policy in two local authority case study areas and were conducted between September 2012 and April 2013. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The research focused on</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> implementation of the</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> academies policy in secondary schools. The first case study is a Metropolitan authority in the North-West of England (hereafter referred to as NW-LA). The research </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">in NW-LA </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">focused on interviewing principals and sponsors of academies which were set up under the New Labour government as well as local authority officers</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> (current and retired)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">. The second case study is a shire county in the East of England (hereafter referred to as E-LA) which has amongst the highest number of secondary</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> school</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> converters in the country. Interviews conducted in E-LA focused on principals and chairs of governors of converter academies and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">current</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">local authority officers. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The research is part of a PhD project funded by the Economic and Social Research Council </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">[grant number ESI01943X/1].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">This submission focuses on 3 aspects highlighted by the inquiry.</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The reasoning behind converter academies’ choice to convert in E-LA</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The local nature of academy sponsors in NW-LA.</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Concerns relating to academy chains voiced in both case study areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Converter Academies: reasoning behind conversion.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.1 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Interviews with local authority officers, academy principals and academy chairs of governors in E-LA explored the reasoning behind schools’ decisions to convert. The three key reasons stated were: </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(1) </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">financial incentives,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> (2)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> fear of isolation and lack of resources, and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(3) </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">reputational risk.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.2 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Financial incentive</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> a governor it’s hard to argue with nearly £1 million going into your school’s infrastructure.” (Academy Chair of Governors)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.3 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The E-LA academies considered in the research converted between March 2011 and February 2012. They therefore received the Local Authority Central Spent Equivalent Grant (LACSEG) before it w</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">as reformed in April 2013 (when </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">the LACSEG</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> was recalculated,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">resulting</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">the reduction of many</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> schools</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">’ LACSEG funding</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">). All interviewees (working in both the local authority and academies) cited the financial advantages of converting to academy status as being</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> either</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> the most decisive</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> factor</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> or amongst the most significant </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">considerations when</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> choosing to convert.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.4 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">This extra money is described as making the policy difficult to argue with and as putting schools in a position where they felt they could not afford </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">not</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> to become an academy. Indeed, the incentives are described in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">a way which</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> suggests schools felt they were almost left with </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">no choice</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> about whether to become involved in the academies policy or not. This, importantly, clashes with the policy’s official narrative of giving greater agency and autonomy to individual schools – instead of feeling empowered to be given a choice over whether to implement a policy, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">many </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">local actors reflect that in practice they were unable to turn down the option of converting to an academy in light of the financial rewards this would bring to their school. In addition, this explanation </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> conversion is at odds with the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> clearly stating that </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">becoming an academy should not bring about a financial advantage or disadvantage to a school.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.5 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Risk of isolation / lack of resources</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 8.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">you</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> have to think about what will happen if we </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">don’t</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> do this [convert to an academy]. And we could become a very isolated school.” (Academy Principal)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.6 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Local authority </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">officers</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">academy</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> principals and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">chairs of </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">governors revealed another factor that affected schools’ decision to convert to academy status was that they anticipated the majority of secondary school</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">s in the local authority area would</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> convert. The fear and sense of risk associated with being in the minority of schools that were not an academy were significant. This concern was based on </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">reasoning that if most schools in the local authority converted to academies the local authority itself would be left with limited resources, leading to a reduced ability to support the remaining schools for which it is </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">still </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">accountable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.7 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Similar to the issue of financial incentives, this sense of risk relating to isolation and lack of resources was characterised by a sense that, while schools were officially given a choice over whether to convert to academy status or not, in actual fact they felt that they had very little choice due to anticipating a situation where they would be disadvantaged by not converting.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.8 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Reputational Risk</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 8.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">there</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> was a sense that good schools were becoming academies. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Erm</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, it was sort of out there in the ether. And therefore you can’t help but feel, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">we’re</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> a good school, we ought to become one too’ […]” (Academy Principal)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 8.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.9</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Another perceived risk associated with not embracing the academies policy was related to the reputation of schools. This factor was emphasised less compared to other considerations</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">owever</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> schools accepted that converter academies come with a reputation of being higher-achieving</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> schools</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> and therefore felt that their own reputations could be at risk if they did not take on the academy label. Again, interviewees </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">placed emphasis on</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> what could happen if their school did </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">not</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> convert to academy status rather than discussing any anticipated changes related to the choice of converting.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.10 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Summary</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">he case study of converter academies in E-LA reveals how schools’ choice to convert was largely based on a sense that financial gains were too </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">substantial</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> to turn down and the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">perceived </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">risks of </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">not</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> converting were too great. These justifications for converting sharply contrast with the official narrative of the academies policy </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">which states that</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> converters will choose to convert exclusively on the grounds that they will be able to enjoy greater freedoms.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Role of Academy Sponsors: a case study of locally focused sponsorship</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">3.1 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The research </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">focused on the nature of the role played by sponsors in academies</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">A key point to emerge</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> was that in this particular case sponsors needed to be understood in terms of the position they occupy in the local area.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Firstly, all interviewees described their decision to become sponsors as being inextricably linked to the role their organisation plays in the local area. Secondly, the involvement of the NW-LA City Counci</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">l as a co-sponsor was crucial in</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> convincing sponsors to become involved with the academies programme. Finally, sponsors demonstrated that their activities often reflected the policy priorities of the NW-LA City Council. I have analysed these issues and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">examined </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">how NW-LA sponsors govern academies in greater detail elsewhere (see </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Papanastasiou</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> (2013)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> reference below).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">3.2 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Another way in which the local </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">nature</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> of NW-LA sponsors is </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">demonstrated</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> relates to their collaboration with principals during the planning stages of the academies. While the NW-LA academies were being set up</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> sponsors and principals worked </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">together </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">on understanding the specific nature of the area which was going to be served by the academy. Creating a strategy for engaging with the local community was described by </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">sponsors and principals as requiring careful consideration of issues such as</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> demography, local history and</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">specific relationships</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> of trust which would all affect how the academy would be </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">regarded by the community</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> engaging with parents in the local area one academy subsequently altered the structure of school terms and holidays to reflect the opinion that a long summer holiday was seen as burdensome for parents who could usually not afford to pay for child care, take holidays or enrol</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> their</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> children in activities. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">3.3 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">NW-LA academy sponsorship has also been set up in collaboration with local partners which has meant that influential local</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> individuals</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">are on</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> these academies’ boards of governors. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Academy principals describe how this equips them with important knowledge about the area in which the academy is located and the communities it serves. For example, one principal emphasised the value of having an executive of the local housing association on the academy board of governors as a way of gaining insights into housing issues that would be affecting students.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Principals and sponsors also emphasised how having local authority officers on their board of governors provided valuable contextual knowledge about the wider social issues – such as the nature of drug problems, transport links and child poverty figures – which are likely to be affecting many academy pupils. Thus, the way in which sponsors </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">are personally invested</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> in the local area and the partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> they have</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> with other local individuals and institutions has been described as equipping NW-LA academies with the resources to deliver an education strategy that is sensitive to locally-specific needs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">3.4 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Summary</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">he academy sponsors included in the NW-LA case study operate and collaborate in a manner that cannot be disconnected from the locality in which they work. This reveals how</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, in order to understand</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> the role of academy sponsors</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, it</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> may </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">be necessary to</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> relat</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> them to their particular local context. However, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">consider</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ations relating to </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">the local context </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">are less</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> likely </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">to be</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> important in the case of other types of academy sponsor, particularly chain sponsors who can operate across a number of geographical areas. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Concerns Relating to Academy Chains</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">4.1 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">While issues around academy chains are not the central focus of the research, almost all policy actors in both case study areas mentioned chains when being interviewed about the implementation of academies. With the exception of one principal who discussed the advantages of economies of scale which exist in chains, all other comments relating to the activities of chains expressed concern. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">4.2 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Concerns over geographical spread</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">A major concern about chains related to those which govern academies over a large geographical area. There was an objection to the idea of running multiple schools with a single model or ethos, largely due to the perception that this did not allow for enough emphasis on local educational needs or for a ‘local solution’ to be brokered </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">in a school. Running an academy using a generic model was framed in a negative light by interviewees as it is perceived to remove local insights from a child’s educational experience. ‘</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ne size fits all’ chain sponsor</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ship</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> was also seen as being ‘imposed’ on schools and th</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">erefore</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">leading to the removal of</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> their individual freedoms. One </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ex-</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">local authority officer described being asked for help by a London-based academy chain which had just acquired a sch</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ool in the north of England. This ex-local authority officer argued that the chain lacked </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">local</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> knowledge which resulted in it struggling with how to go about supporting the school. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Thus, there is a perceived contradiction between localism and the spread of national academy chains. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">4.3 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Concerns over accountability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">There was also a widespread concern amongst interviewees regarding </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">a lack of information about</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">how and why executives are motivated to run academy chains. The perceived link between </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">the salaries of </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">some executives and the number of academies in their chains was unanimously considered unacceptable because it was </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">thought</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> to be emphasising chain growth over the delivery of educational quality. An associated concern is that chains and their executives are accountable to their company rather than the local community served by an individual academy. It was generally </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">considered</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> that sponsors from the local area and the local authority its</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">elf have a commitment to</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> local communities which was not understood to be the case with chain sponsors. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">4.4 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Concerns over governance</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Academy principals and chairs of governors argued that they would prefer not to be sponsored by a chain due to</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> the nature of their</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> governance structures. One interviewee discussed how some chains have started to take powers out of an academy’s board of governors and lift these to a ‘higher level’ which they saw as problematic due to decision-making becoming detached from the immediate school context. This governance structure was also linked back to concerns over decisions not being representative of local community interests</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> board of governors consisting of local representatives such as parents and community members</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> was suggested to be more representative of a local community</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">. One principal also objected to the idea of being part of an academy chain by arguing that there would be less autonomy for principals due to the central </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">management of academy functions </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">which would </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">normally </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">carried out at the school level. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">4.5 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Summary</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Central to these concerns regarding academy chains is the perception that they </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">disconnect schools </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> education</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> that is locally sensitive</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reference</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Papanastasiou</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, N. 2013. ‘Commercial Actors and the Governing of Education: the case of academy school sponsors in England.’ </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">European Educational Research Journal</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> 12(4): 447-462.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>